metadata.name: Tesseract Visions #129
metadata.description:
Tesseract Visions is an abstract generative artwork inspired by the movie Interstellar.

''The Tesseract is an enormous, hyper-cubic, grid-like structure and a means of communication for the bulk beings to express action through gravity with NASA. The bulk beings can perceive five dimensions instead of four, able to see every moment in the past, present, and future. The bulk beings can influence gravity within any of those time frames.''
(https://interstellarfilm.fandom.com/wiki/Tesseract)

The work presents the observation of the universe from a tesseract. I tried to symbolize the past through form of sketches and drawings, the present with a current view inside the Tesseract, and the future with the occasional showing of supernovas and black holes in some iterations.

It's amazing how far we've come as a human race, from sketching with charcoal to coding, from walking through the desert to traveling through space.

I hope that this chaotic collection will make sense to you despite its illogicality.


Options:

- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 'd' to save a hi-res PNG image

Created using p5.js
Bajiru, July 2023.

metadata.name: Mini Dahlias #120
metadata.description:
Welcome to the enchanting world of "Mini Dahlias" - a mesmerizing generative art project that will spark joy in your heart! Unleashing the magic of algorithms, each miniature masterpiece blooms with vibrant colors and whimsical patterns, transporting you to a dreamy realm of creativity.

But wait, there's more to this fantastical journey! Nestled within each digital artwork lies a hidden treasure - an embedded blueprint that holds the secret to crafting a tangible, real-life edition. Picture it: delicate petals brought to life in the physical realm, ready to be gifted or cherished!

Twenty exquisite physical editions of “mini Dahlias,” crafted with love are destined to be gifted by a friend of mine to random strangers at Burning Man, where creativity knows no bounds!

Inspired by spreading joy and creativity, "Mini Dahlias" is available on fxhash, ensuring that this delightful experience can be enjoyed by art enthusiasts worldwide. Embrace the charm, share the magic, and let the artistry of algorithms paint smiles across the universe. Happy creating and sharing the wonder! 🎨✨

metadata.name: PolyGarden #78
metadata.description:
Polygons, patterns and flowers are mixtured in my garden. I start with a birdeye view of the garden and its geometric structure. The species diversity and the random stack of rocks, sands, fences and other objects are main structures I want to capture, in an abstract and planar style. 

Moreover, in this project, I also try to explore the representation ability of generative art. I select three elements: shape of entity, layout of palette, and stack of object location. The factors behind these elements are the balance of randomness and structure: the generative art generates the variants from randomness but restricts its chaos with structure (deterministic constraints) to represent the meaningful results. 

Variables:
- 4 layouts
- 6 texture patterns
- 15 color palette
- 3 randomness
- 2 completeness

Please be patient with drawing process.

metadata.name: Furrr #51

Inspired by natural macro structures, I experimented to create a hairy, soft, tactile surface, using gradient colors and overlays. The curves are an optical illusion, no curved lines are used.

metadata.name: an abstract concept #18
metadata.description:
I often try to duplicate my IRL analog abstract painting in code, and this, like my previous mint "a fleeting moment," is an attempt at that. Or it started that way. As is usual with such things, it quickly took on a life of its own. 

The algorithm itself consists of three layers of the main particle abstraction, which comes in five different styles, and roughly eight layers of the "texture," which comes in three styles. The palette consists of the background color and three colors for the particle algorithm. The texture is always drawn with the first of those three colors (the "base" color.) 

The result is indicative of my normal painting style (I almost always use three color layers over a background color, and paint with a spatula, palette knife, or cake knife) but is its own unique look.
